Apparently it says it contains 638 mg of Ornithine, that's the amino acid that helps turn ammonia into urea. Once capsule is generally only 250-500 mg. But it's also involved in cell division (ornithine decarboxylase) so too much all the time would probably be a bit dangerous.

Haidut had some Japanese study with middle aged people who felt better after taking 500 mg Ornithine, but said something like Ceylon Cinnamon is probably a safer way to get NH3 down. Ornithine-aspartate in 2-14 g doses is used as a drug for cirrhosis patients apparently, "LOLA".

I just realized that Georgi Dinkov used to talk about how Sodium Benzoate (which is used as a food preservative and they put it in canned foods) also reduces ammonia, but Ceylon cinnamon is actually metabolized into Sodium Benzoate in the body... So it's basically the same thing.
Haidut's practical recommendation for most people was just 2 grams of Ceylon cinnamon together with something sweet before going to bed if you don't care about the chemical stuff.

For the record this is not something you ought to have every single day anyways, ammonia takes some time to build up again afterwards, even having half a teaspoon of Ceylon cinnamon once a week with whatever dessert is probably more than enough for the possible health benefits...

Celine also formulated sleep aid tablets called "Somnothyril", which also contained thyroid. Not surprising if you remember Dr. Ray Peat talking about how just a few mcg of T3 can knock you out immediately, but no one would think of putting thyroid in an anti-insomnia drug today.

Although the sleep drug also contained Physostigmine which is a highly cholinergic substance that can actually mimic the "learned helplessness" shock state produced by inescapable stress. Some French patriot Dr. Ray Peat fan should write an article series on Dr. Celine's drugs...
